Fig. 6 E , F
). After settlement, dwarf male metamorphoses within carapace, shed cypris cuticle with thoracopods coming to lie in posterior part (
Fig. 6 D , E
). Newly developed young dwarf male globular, with short posterior end terminating in distinct apertural slit (
Fig. 6 G , H
), bearing antennules of typical cypris morphology, and lacking long attachment stalk (
